<h1>Symphyotrichum novi-belgii – New York Aster</h1>

<p>
<a href="/o/page?o=word&w=Aster">Aster</a> novi-belgii is a perennial wildflower known for its vibrant late-season blooms in shades of purple, pink, and blue.
</p>

<h2>Description</h2>
<p>
Produces dense clusters of small daisy-like flowers on upright stems. Often forms bushy clumps in gardens and wild habitats.
</p>

<h2>Etymology</h2>
<p>
“Novae-belgii” refers to “New Belgium,” the historical name for the New York region during Dutch colonization.
</p>

<h2>Taxonomy</h2>
<p>
Family: Asteraceae<br>
Genus: Symphyotrichum<br>
Species: S. novi-belgii
</p>

<h2>Distribution and Habitat</h2>
<p>
Native to eastern North America, especially coastal and meadow regions with moist soils.
</p>

<h2>Ecology</h2>
<p>
Provides late-season nectar and pollen for bees and migrating butterflies.
</p>

<h2>Cultivation</h2>
<ul>
<li>Full sun</li>
<li>Moist, well-drained soil</li>
<li>Regular division helps maintain vigor</li>
</ul>

<h3>Cultivars</h3>
<ul>
<li>‘Marie Ballard’</li>
<li>‘Professor Anton Kippenberg’</li>
</ul>

<h2>Symbolism</h2>
<p>
Represents patience, memory, and the arrival of autumn.
</p>

